title: Filament Spool + Ultimaker Spool Holder + Wall Spool Holder
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: With all those loose pieces of filament laying around this is just what you need! It's a simple, strong and quite big filament spool with an Ultimaker attachment to hold your spools. They are quite stack-able but we also included wall mounts, this way you can be your own 'West Coast Customs' but with filament spools instead of rims on the wall.

The filament spools themselves can be laser cut out of a 3mm plate. You need three of each component, 9 M3x16 bolts and 9 M3 nuts. In the STL you can see how they lock into each other. But who would make one when you can have 10 of them!? That's why we also included 2 plates for a 600x300mm laser cutter with nested parts to create 10 at once!

The Ultimaker spool holders consist of three parts which are held together with some M3 bolts and nuts. This sandwich can be attached to the upper-left-back corner of an Ultimaker (opposite to the extruder drive). You have to take out the two bolts in the corner and replace them with some that are just a bit longer (M3x20) to attach the part.

Last but not least we have even attached some wall mount spool holders. Now you can pimp up your room and show off your filament. It's a basic print and you can fiddle with your slicer settings all you like. We printed them on our Ultimakers using a 0,8mm nozzle and a layer thickness of 0,2.

title: Sony NEX-5 Camera Screen Sun Shield

description.text:
I've had this camera for years and I love the thing. But shooting pictures in bright sunlight is a challenge because mine doesn't have a viewfinder.   
So, now it does. I have only had a few mins in the sun to test it out but it certainly makes it much easier to use. I'll test it for awhile and decide if I need to increase the size of the shield to better cover the screen. In which case you will see an update here.  
For me to snap it on I first slid the right side in, then snapped the left side in. I then slid the cover down another 1cm or so to fit it over the screen. The lcd screen still moves freely except it no longer sits flush against the camera. It sticks out about 7mm. Also the menu and option buttons are just slightly covered. Not enough to brother myself. Just so you know if case you think there was a printing mistake.  
This was specifically designed to fit around the lcd screen of the NEX-5. Which pulls out and rotates up and down. If you need this for a different model you'll have to look at the stl file and see if it will fit. If your still not sure print just the clip on part and then stop the print and try it out.

The stl file needs to rotated 90 degrees so that the top part is flat on the bed. You can then print the whole thing without supports.  
I used 0.2mm at 50mm/s

title: Blower Fan Duct for Wanhao, Flashforge, CTC etc

description.text: This is a rehash of Alessandro's http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:795992 Wanhao Duplicator 4/4x Filament Fan Duct. When I printed his version I found the part pushed against the belt. I also decided to make some changes so the parts could be printed without supports. Lightly sand the parts where they will be glued together. Print using ABS and not PLA. This is helpful for two reasons. One, the heat of the nozzle will melt the lower portion closest to the heat source and Two, use ABS Juice to glue the parts together. Print using ABS, .3 Layer and 30% Infill. Build Plate heated to 110. I use a sheet of glass on my build plate and find that hair spray is the perfect medium to ensure parts stay on the glass. I usually put on two coats of hair spray. I'm using Suave Extra Hold. EDIT: I found the hole for the left screw was not lined up properly and made an adjustment.

title: Cable wraper for laptop bag (or desk drawer)

description.text: My laptop bag is a mess with a dozen different USB, Lightning, iPhone, etc. cables. None of the other cable wrappers I found were quite right. This is about my 6th iteration of the design, and it seems to work quite well without putting undue stress on the wires. The idea is that you can wrap a cable up fully, and selectively unwrap a few coils to get various cable lengths easily. Multiple wrappers also snap together, and can be twisted to form closed pentagonal/hexagonal assemblies (see photos). Note, there is a sister project (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:813482) with dongle holders that use the same snap together system. This should print very easily without support. As a consequence, when snapping them together there is ~1mm offset, but seems fine to me. If the loops at the ends are too tight for a particular cable, I suggest just trimming the end of the loop a bit. I think this should scale pretty well for larger wires, but haven't tried it. I will post modified versions later if scaling doesn't work well.

Should work well without support in any plastic. Might consider starting with 2 and doing a test-fit to make sure your print tolerances are right for the snap-together aspect to work well. On my Taz, I can easily print 10 at a go.

description.text:
HobbyKing sells a low budget DIY FPV mask under the Quanum brand. I liked the idea of using a display with a lens in front of it. The picture is so much more immersive than with FPV googles. And the low price is a huge bonus too. But there are things with the Quanum mask that suck. The screen is ultra low resolution. The mask uses a Fresnel lens which makes it impossible to obtain a sharp image. Fresnel lenses are unsuited for use in anything close to the eyes. High magnification reading glasses provide better sharpness, but are not so easy to mount in the Quanum mask. There were a few 3D-printed mask designs available, but none of them allowed for using reading glasses. They also seemed rather heavy. As a result I decided to build my own mask out of foam and 3D-printed parts. Instead of cutting out the main body parts from foam, I decided to buy them ready made from http://flyingwings.co.uk/fpv-uav/fpv-eco-goggles.html. The parts turned out to be of high quality and made out of very durable black foam. I highly recommend using these rather than cutting or printing your own. It is possible to use up to a 5 inch 16x9 screen. I then designed the 3D-printed parts needed to mount a three point head band, reading glasses, cabling and the screen to the mask. I am using a Boscam FR632 receiver. I have designed a holder for it that can be found here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:788540 I used 4x reading glasses that I bought locally in Sweden at Clas Ohlson and modified by cutting the frame. I am sure that it will be possible to find similar glasses pretty much everywhere. The screen I used is a 5 inch variant with 800x480 resolution. This particular screen does not go into bluescreen mode when the signal is low, which is a must for FPV. http://www.banggood.com/Blue-Sky-5-Inch-HD-Digital-Panel-Display-800x480-Snowflakes-Screen-p-970382.html
I am providing alternative mask fronts both for the screen I used and a generic variant that can be used with any screen by manually cutting out a hole to make it fit. The only modification to the screen is that I drilled two holes in the back plate for the cabling and replaced the original clumsy cables. I made a back cover for my particular screen that hides the cable holes. The head band is made from a 2 inch (5 cm) elastic belt. Total cost for the mask (not including the receiver) was about 60 Euro. My 32 channel diversity receiver was another 60 Euro. But you can find 8 channel 5.8 GHz receivers for well under 20$ today, which is kind of amazing. All parts are small enough to fit on a 15x15 printing bed.

comments.text: Yes, it will work for you. But even if you have 2020 vision you will need glasses in masks (at least if you are over the age of 10 or so). The minimum focus distance deteriorates throughout life. I am 50 and have normal sight form my age. This means that I need reading glasses of strength +1 to read normal text. Reading glasses of strength +3 to +4 work perfectly for me in the mask. Younger people who normally do not need reading glasses need +1 to +2 reading glasses to get perfect sharpness in the mask. The reason is that the screen is closer to the eye than any adult will be able to focus.

About image quality: Using single magnifying lenses has the unavoidable effect of producing slight barrel distortion. But this is the only quality issue. Reading glasses are very sharp indeed. Much better than using Fresnel lenses.
Does the monitor go to blue screen?: No, the monitor I link in the description does not go to blue screen. As long as there is a trace of a signal, you see it. Perfect for FPV.
Why not place the receiver closer to the monitor?: It would be a poor idea to place the heavy diversity receiver where the screen is.
